text: ???: I know what you did.
Manaia: Huh?
???: I overhead everything. And I want in.
???: The name's Blorbo.
Manaia: Can I trust you?
Blorbo: Yes.

Fionn: You alright? It's you ain't it? You're dressed in the garb I sent you.
Manaia: Fionn? What you said about your sister—
Fionn: No time. I won't be able to say the rest if we continue that.
Fionn: Pierre Jean Faust, the host of this, has us servants under strict orders. The bastard. Before long someone'll come looking.
Manaia: Us servants?
Fionn: I wanted to do it myself. From the inside. It was the only way I could think, but... god.
Fionn: Sorry... I... you don't know what they've been saying round here.
Manaia: Slow down. Tell me from the beginning.
Manaia: Are you implying what I think you are?
Manaia: What have they been saying?
Manaia: What have they been saying?
Fionn: Psh whateveerrrr
Fionn: They've been trying to cover something up. Don't want anyone talking about it during the festivities. But that hasn't stopped some of the hearsay.

Fionn: Been an accident round the time Niamh went missing. Was a huge mess of a thing. Took lives from some maids and nearly the whole underbelly of the Mansion. The usual docking area for ships is still under repair.
Fionn: Even so, other than me 'an the few working, the rest couldn't give two dog licks. I'd bleach their tongues clean if I could.
Manaia: Are you implying what I think you are?
Manaia: Are you implying what I think you are?
Manaia: ...
Fionn: They're calling it an accident but it's muddier than that. I asked some of the others about Niamh but none of 'em could even recall her name.
Fionn: She has been working here though, told me herself.
Fionn: The problem is, Sir Faust and all these other rich pricks are interested in some dingy stuff. This whole auction's underground, not many Fleur du Cielian's could tell you about it.
Fionn: Ain't hard to recognise the guests here though, even from voice alone. He's invited every bigshot around to bid on his strange collection of junk.
Fionn:Not much I can do. I'd be sent, ass first, off the ledge if I tried talking to any of 'em.
Manaia: So this is where I come in?
Fionn: Exactly... well.. that isn't to say it'll be easier for you.
Fionn: As an unknown here, it'll take a bit to get people to talk without causing suspicion. Get their trust. Tell them things they want to hear. Or find another way around.
Fionn: Look, it won't be long before the first night of bidding starts. Find out as much as you can and I'll get you after. We can't be seen together once we're inside.
Manaia: I won't let you down.
Fionn: Good luck.
Fionn: Despite everything, I'm glad you're here.
Manaia: ...

Strange Person: I know what you are.
Strange Person: I heard everything, the two of you talking outside.
Crap
Strange Person: You’re foreign intelligence, aren’t you?
Manaia: ...
Strange Person: Ah, Silence.
Strange Person: It’s alright, I’m rather good at reading between the lines.
Manaia: I'm really not.
Manaia: I'm really not.
Strange Person: You’re looking for your partner, right? Your fellow agent?
Manaia: I’m not a spy.
It’s much more complicated than that.
Manaia: We were practising parts for a play.
Manaia: We were practising parts for a play.
Strange Person: Of course, of course, you were practising.
If you could see his face, you think he'd be winking right now.
Manaia: I'm a safety inspector. Investigating... the accident.
Manaia:I'm a safety inspector. Investigating... the accident.
Strange Person: An inspector, huh? An... undercover inspector?
Manaia: Are you going to tell someone?
Manaia: Are you going to tell someone?
Strange Person: Hmm? Why would I?
Manaia: What do you want from me?
Manaia: What do you want from me?
Strange Person: I think we should be pals. You and I.
Strange Person: To see a professional at work, would be an unmissable opportunity.
Strange Person: For the both of us!
Strange Person: One moment.
He reaches for your journal.
Manaia: Wait, what are you—
Reaching into one pocket, he pulls out a pen and starts scrawling something on a blank page.
He hands it back. It reads Claude Dupont in large, cursive lettering.
Claude: My signature. After I release my next novel, this will be priceless.
Claude: How lucky for us to have met. Espionage is quite a popular genre nowadays.
Claude: You don't mind if I tag along right? For research?
Who the hell is this guy?
Claude: Great! Don't mind me. Act as if I'm not even here.
Manaia: Not yet. There's still some places I should check out on this floor.

Manaia: Interesting, how did they get a hold of such extinct material.
Bartender: Could I be so kind in offering you a drink?
Manaia: I'm fine thank you, just taking a look at this instillation.
Bartender: Oh yes, our Host is very fond of this new flora matter that they've discovered.
Display Attendant: What we have here is a catagory B item. Lethe's Blessing.
Display Attendant: A rare flower, local to the coastlines of Mórport, the City of Soot.
Display Attendant: When crushed and mixed into a drink, it has a tart but agreeable taste.
Display Attendant: Enjoy intoxicated bliss, and be rid of the painful memories which haunt you!
Display Attendant: You only need a spoonful, to experience its full effects.
You recognise this flower. Lethe's blessing... what an underhanded name. Lethe's curse is closer. A blight upon your hometown. It's hardly the "rare" wonder he's advertising it as.
Experience minute brain damage... and become addicted to transforming yourself into a drooling vegetable.
Warn them.
Manaia: Thats not—
Before you can finish, you're interruppted by sharp laughter.
Stay Silent.
As the attendant is about to continue, he's interrupted by sharp laughter.
Display Attendent: Sir...?
Display Attendant: I appreciate your glee, but I assure you this is no tent show.
Mysterious Stranger: Oh, no no. This is good stuff. Lethe's blessing was it? Delightful. Pierre is simply showing anything this year.
Mysterious Stranger: Can't very well expect him to outdo himself every time I suppose. Merely plants more dullards for the next.
Display Attendant: I'm sorry?
Mysterious Stranger: Do go on. I can scarcely wait to see this completely run to seed.
Display Attendant: Ah... Well.
Display Attendant: Lethe's Blessing is... This particular plant's history, yes.
Servant1: We've had some strange things happen.  "That place" has been a lot more active...and not in a good way
Servant2: No, no, we're not talking occult during work time again. Let's just get this to the next room.
Manaia: Three's a crowd, huh? Seems they won't talk with me here.
Servant 1: I’m telling you. Ever since that day, I’ve been losing things, tripping over nothing, I broke five plates yesterday. She has it out for me!
Servant 2: That’s just you being a clutz.
Servant 1: No, honest.  Everytime it happens, I keep seeing her. Drab as always and scowling at me something terrible.
Servant 1: You think it's cause I made her clean The Four’s rooms for me so I could nab some of her hairpins? Not like I'd know she'd get her brains blown out.
Servant 2: What! How could you?
Servant 2: I had dibs on those!
Display Attendant: Magnificent is it not? The Brimstone's Beacon flower is truely a sight to behold.
Display Attendant: You ought to have many questions about it, I'm sure.
Manaia: I have a different question in mind.
Manaia: Do you-
Manaia: Not really.
Display Attendant: Of course you do! You must be grateful Sir Faust has even allowed you to view an item such as this.
Display Attendant: To think, a plant could survive in the Sepulchral Fog. So near to core of our planet, to The Veiled Maw.  It is a wonder of wonders.

Display Attendant: Only the most seasoned of helmsman could have navigated their crew through those thick turbulent mists. And only one with a ship built for the pressure. Not many have been so lucky.
Display Attendant: This is truely a one of a kind item, the highest ranking in our catalogue.
Display Attendant: When distilled, it creates a biofuel beyond any we've seen before.  As an energy source it is thought to be capable of commencing an entirely new technological age!
Display Attendant: Isn't that facinating?
Manaia: Sure is. Now my question....
Manaia: Wait, I don't really care about this.
It's like his ears are packed with cotton.
Display Attendant: And that's not all!
Display Attendant: It has been rumoured to carry some of the illusionary qualities of the fog itself.

Display Attendant: Though perhaps less dramatic than the cries for help one might hear while flying through the Sepulchral fog, it is still quite a coveted item for anyone interested in the occult. Or perhaps the scientifically inclined?
He takes a breath. Nows your chance!
Manaia: Ask about "recent events".
Manaia: I heard there was an accident in the docking area. What can you tell me about that?
Display Attendant: Eh? The explosion?
Display Attendant: Crap. You made me lose my train of thought. What part of the script was I up to?
Manaia: Walk away (End Conversation)
Manaia: What is this? A side effect from Brimstone's Beacon?
Manaia: This song...
Niamh: Manaia…
Niamh: You idiot! What are you doing here?
Manaia: Niamh?
Niamh: Take Fionn and leave. You should have never come here.
Manaia: Is this real?
Manaia: Is this real?
Manaia: This isn't real.
Manaia: This isn't real.
Manaia: This isn't real.
Manaia:What is this?
Niamh: I’m not sure how you opened this… doorway, but I could care less.
Niamh: I don't need you here. You're letting Fionn lead you both to your death.
Manaia: I’m not leaving you.
Niamh: You’re not– You’re…
She laughs bitterly. Then rakes her hands down her face.
Niamh: You always do this. You’re always stubborn at the worst of times.
Niamh: We’re never going back to the way we were. It’s impossible, Manaia.
Manaia: I have something to say to you. But I’ll only say it to your face.
Niamh: You don’t get it. It’s too late for that. Don’t pry any more. You can’t do anything for me.
Niamh: Manaia. If I ever meant anything to you, you would listen. Give up.
Manaia: This isn’t real, I’m not listening to you.
Manaia: This isn’t real, I’m not listening to you.
Niamh: You’re a fool. This is so much bigger than you and your stupid hero complex.
Manaia: Let me help you.
Manaia: Let me help you.
Niamh: You’re a fool. This is so much bigger than you and your stupid hero complex.
Manaia: If it’s like the fog, that must've been a mirage.
Manaia: A waking dream fabricated by the universe. Just to trick me into giving up on her. But why?
Claude: Outstanding performance! Was that a monologue?
Manaia: ...
Claude: The determination! The confusion! It was like a punch to the gut!
Claude: One piece of criticism though, your script was just awful. Made no sense.

Servant: What exactly do you mean.?

Disgruntled Woman: The catalogue is so limited this year. Plants this, flowers that. Where are the exotic animals, the ancient artefacts, the banned books?
Her Husband: Apologies, dearest. I didn’t realise they’d only had Monsieur Faust’s botanic collection on hand, after well…
Disgruntled Woman: How drab. One person blows up an airship and It becomes everyone else’s problem.
Manaia: Someone blew up an airship?
Manaia: You two know Faust?
Disgruntled Woman: Oh, that's old news.
Disgruntled Woman: Quite the scandal. I think he's rather embarrased about it.
Disgruntled Woman: That someone would slight him like that.
Disgruntled Woman: Calls it an "accident".
Disgruntled Woman: Yes, an accident.
Disgruntled Woman: A man with that sort of money? Ought to have brought a fine ship.
Her Husband: Very fine.
Disgruntled Woman: And for it to go kerflooey, just like that?
The woman's husband mimics an explosion with his hands.
Disgruntled Woman: Well, that is when a conspiracy is afoot.
Her Husband: Afoot indeed.
Disgruntled Woman: Percy?
Her Husband: Yes dear?
Disgruntled Woman: Shut up.
Her Husband: Yes dear.
Disgruntled Woman: Know Faust? How else would we be here?
Disgruntled Woman: If I take it you mean intimately, well... one does not simply "know" Sir Faust.
Disgruntled Woman: Unless you're one of The Four.
Disgruntled Woman: Who are you anyway? A first-timer?
Manaia: Yep, that's me. A first-timer.
Manaia: Second time, actually.
Disgruntled Woman: I see...
Disgruntled Woman: Well, I can't say I'd reccomend this year as your first.
Disgruntled Woman: Normally it's far more interesting.
Disgruntled Woman: Hmm... I don't think I've seen you around here.
Disgruntled Woman: Though I suppose it's hard to tell with the mask.
Disgruntled Women: Percy, be a darling and get me a drink. I'm getting bored.
Her Husband: I don't think that wise, my sweet.
Disgruntled Woman: Pish posh. Don't be wet blanket.
Her Husband: After the last event, I don't think they'll allow you or me near the bar.
You wonder if you can squeeze any information from of them. Before they get distracted any further.
Manaia: Who are The Four?
Manaia: What else do you know about the accident?
Manaia: I've been hearing that title all around.
Disgruntled Woman: Oh, this really is your first time! How were you even invited?
Disgruntled Woman: Have you absolutely gone to one of these before? That's common knowlege!
Disgruntled Woman: These auctions really are going to the dogs.
Disgruntled Woman: If you expect me to tell you that, it would take all day. And I don't give out history classes for free.
Disgruntled Woman: All I'll tell you, is that our latest host is one of them.
Manaia: Latest host?
Disgruntled Woman: Now, you're really asking too much of me.
Disgruntled Woman: I'm not a tutor.
The woman sighs.
Disgruntled Woman: Very well as much as anyone else, but more than you I presume.
Disgruntled Woman:  I'll tell you what.
Disgruntled Woman: If you can sweet talk a drink for me from the bar, I'll say anything you very well please.
Disgruntled Woman: If I'm to be harassed like a presidential candidate with a mistress, I'd at least want something to swig while you're at it.
The woman's husband begins to fidget, but seems to have given up on urging otherwise.
Manaia: Any drink preferences?
Manaia: Thank you. I'll find you something.
Disgruntled Woman: Surprise me! Whatever you do, just make it strong.
Disgruntled Woman: If if doesn't bite back, I will.
The woman laughs, but something tells you she's not entirely joking.
Manaia: I've never seen a machine like that.
Bartender: The distiller?
Bartender:	You'll be hard-pressed to find another machine like it.
Bartender:	It's custom-made.
Bartender:	Runs on the highest quality Evergreen fuel and expertly processes plants from Sir Faust's private collection.
Bartender: The beverages on offer are one of a kind.
Bartender:	Carefully designed from the sowing of the ingredients themselves!
Bartender:	Might I interest you in one?
